00:43:32.309 --> 00:43:37.498
Okay, now I'm going to return
to the conductors briefly to

00:43:37.498 --> 00:43:39.409
tell you something.
 

00:43:39.409 --> 00:43:42.730
One other thing that is new
compared to what we did before.

00:43:42.730 --> 00:43:45.130
Remember what I told you about
a conductor?

00:43:45.130 --> 00:43:49.985
A conductor is one in which the
electrons do not belong to any

00:43:49.985 --> 00:43:51.018
one parent.
 

00:43:51.018 --> 00:43:54.431
They run around to the whole
sample, but they cannot leave

00:43:54.431 --> 00:43:55.150
the metal.
 

00:43:55.150 --> 00:43:57.273
At the boundary of the metal
there are forces bringing them

00:43:57.273 --> 00:43:57.530
back.
 

00:43:57.530 --> 00:43:59.570
Inside they are free to move.
 

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:02.945
Therefore, if you take a
conductor and you stick it into

00:44:02.945 --> 00:44:06.260
a field initially the electric
field will penetrate the

00:44:06.260 --> 00:44:07.119
conductor.
 

00:44:07.119 --> 00:44:09.094
The charges,
because they are free to move,

00:44:09.094 --> 00:44:09.659
will move.
 

00:44:09.659 --> 00:44:11.050
The negatives charges will move
one way,

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:14.722
positive charges will move the
other way until they set up a

00:44:14.722 --> 00:44:18.023
back reaction to this that
blocks the field inside the

00:44:18.023 --> 00:44:20.389
metal until the field inside is
0.

00:44:20.389 --> 00:44:23.429
So here's a generic conductor.
 

00:44:23.429 --> 00:44:29.161
If you put it in an external
field it will have some charges

00:44:29.161 --> 00:44:33.197
on its surface,
will produce a field this way

00:44:33.197 --> 00:44:37.931
that will oppose the external
field in which you put it until

00:44:37.931 --> 00:44:41.719
at the end there's no field
inside the metal.

00:44:41.719 --> 00:44:44.530
Or, if you did not put it in
the field and just took this

00:44:44.530 --> 00:44:46.590
material and dumped some charge
on it,

00:44:46.590 --> 00:44:49.869
threw some charge on it and
asked where does it go,

00:44:49.869 --> 00:44:53.429
well, the charges are all plus
and they don't like each other.

00:44:53.429 --> 00:44:56.704
They want to move away from
each other, and they move as far

00:44:56.704 --> 00:45:00.090
as they can until they come to
the boundary and they cannot go

00:45:00.090 --> 00:45:00.980
any further.
 

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:03.219
That's where they stop.
 

00:45:03.219 --> 00:45:06.152
That we saw before,
so we know all the charges in

00:45:06.152 --> 00:45:08.110
the metal are in the boundary.
 

00:45:08.110 --> 00:45:11.159
There is no electric field
inside because of Gauss's Law.

00:45:11.159 --> 00:45:14.413
If I want to find the charge
here I do a tiny sphere and do

00:45:14.413 --> 00:45:16.768
integral
E⋅da.

00:45:16.768 --> 00:45:19.320
I get 0, and that's the charge
inside.

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:21.750
And I can move this little
microscope all over the inside.

00:45:21.750 --> 00:45:23.250
I keep getting zero.
 

00:45:23.250 --> 00:45:26.219
That's why I know there's no
charge inside.

00:45:26.219 --> 00:45:27.500
There's no charge inside.
 

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:28.750
There is no field inside.
 

00:45:28.750 --> 00:45:33.960
Q = 0 inside metal.
 

00:45:33.960 --> 00:45:41.730
This is a solid metal,
and E = 0 inside solid.

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:48.476
The other variation you can
have is suppose they make a hole

00:45:48.476 --> 00:45:49.619
in this.
 

00:45:49.619 --> 00:45:52.606
There is no electric field
anywhere here because it's a

00:45:52.606 --> 00:45:53.050
metal.
 

00:45:53.050 --> 00:45:55.822
The whole logic is if you've
got a field you're not in a

00:45:55.822 --> 00:45:56.780
static situation.
 

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:58.010
Let the charges move.
 

00:45:58.010 --> 00:46:00.320
They'll keep moving until they
have no reason to move.

00:46:00.320 --> 00:46:03.090
That reason will stop when the
field vanishes.

00:46:03.090 --> 00:46:03.650
It's quite amazing.
 

00:46:03.650 --> 00:46:06.844
They can always find an
arrangement in which they kill

00:46:06.844 --> 00:46:08.110
the external field.
 

00:46:08.110 --> 00:46:09.159
That's the perfect metal.
 

00:46:09.159 --> 00:46:10.699
So there's no field here.
 

00:46:10.699 --> 00:46:16.590
So if you do a Gaussian surface
like this the charge inside that

00:46:16.590 --> 00:46:19.556
is 0,
but that does not preclude the

00:46:19.556 --> 00:46:24.289
possibility that there are maybe
some plus charges there and some

00:46:24.289 --> 00:46:25.989
minus charges there.
 

00:46:25.989 --> 00:46:31.246
Last time I told you that if
that happens then the pluses and

00:46:31.246 --> 00:46:36.327
minuses will run around and meet
and destroy each other and

00:46:36.327 --> 00:46:39.041
neutralize,
but that's a little subtle

00:46:39.041 --> 00:46:42.068
because maybe if they were the
only two things in the world I

00:46:42.068 --> 00:46:44.927
can understand that,
but there's also these charges

00:46:44.927 --> 00:46:47.289
outside maybe that'll impede
their motion.

00:46:47.289 --> 00:46:50.123
But here's one way to prove
that there can be really no

00:46:50.123 --> 00:46:51.960
charge even on the inner
surface.

00:46:51.960 --> 00:46:54.688
If there were some plus charges
here and minus charges

00:46:54.688 --> 00:46:57.574
there--remember Q is 0
inside so you can only have

00:46:57.574 --> 00:46:58.449
equal number.
 

00:46:58.449 --> 00:47:02.081
Then electric field lines will
have to leave the plus charge

00:47:02.081 --> 00:47:04.360
and terminate on the minus
charge,

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:07.360
so there'll be an electric
field inside the cavity,

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:10.896
and I'm saying that's not
allowed because of the

00:47:10.896 --> 00:47:11.800
following.
 

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:15.639
If there is a field inside the
cavity let's take that path and

00:47:15.639 --> 00:47:19.289
another path which are two ways
to go from here to here.

00:47:19.289 --> 00:47:22.240
On one path I get a line
integral of E to be not

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:22.460
0.
 

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:25.608
Second one I get line integral
equal to 0 because there is no

00:47:25.608 --> 00:47:28.860
E, but the line integral
cannot vary with the path in an

00:47:28.860 --> 00:47:30.329
electrostatic situation.
 

00:47:30.329 --> 00:47:34.514
Therefore, there cannot be any
electric field inside the cavity

00:47:34.514 --> 00:47:36.809
due to anything you put outside.
 

00:47:36.809 --> 00:47:41.186
You can have an electric field
inside the cavity if you go into

00:47:41.186 --> 00:47:44.929
the cavity and put by hand some
extra charge there.

00:47:44.929 --> 00:47:48.228
Then what will happen is that
guy will produce a field and the

00:47:48.228 --> 00:47:51.364
field lines will come to the
boundary and terminate on some

00:47:51.364 --> 00:47:52.500
negative charges.
 

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:54.860
Again, there'll be no field
here.

00:47:54.860 --> 00:48:02.744
But a hollow cavity with no
charges inside the hole will not

00:48:02.744 --> 00:48:07.289
have charges on the edge either.
 

00:48:07.289 --> 00:48:09.849
So now, what else can we say
about conductors?

00:48:09.849 --> 00:48:13.431
Today I used the fact that the
line integral of E is 0

00:48:13.431 --> 00:48:16.655
to tell you that in a hollow
cavity you cannot have any

00:48:16.655 --> 00:48:18.090
charges in the wall.
 

00:48:18.090 --> 00:48:27.320
Second thing is every conductor
is an equipotential.

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:33.309
It's an equipotential.
 

00:48:33.309 --> 00:48:33.940
Why is that?
 

00:48:33.940 --> 00:48:39.637
Can you tell me why that is
true if it is not equipotential,

00:48:39.637 --> 00:48:41.280
the whole lump?
 

00:48:41.280 --> 00:48:42.900
Yep?
 

00:48:42.900 --> 00:48:44.635
Student:  If it wasn't
equal potential then there would

00:48:44.635 --> 00:48:45.659
be an electric field inside
there.

00:48:45.659 --> 00:48:46.989
Prof: And how do we know
that?

00:48:46.989 --> 00:48:49.275
Student:  Because
there's a potential difference

00:48:49.275 --> 00:48:50.079
________________.
 

00:48:50.079 --> 00:48:51.510
Prof: That's right.
 

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:53.239
In other words,
if you take the gradient,

00:48:53.239 --> 00:48:55.226
namely taking derivatives,
you'll get a non-zero

00:48:55.226 --> 00:48:57.849
derivative because I'm telling
you V is not constant.

00:48:57.849 --> 00:48:59.590
In some direction it's got to
change.

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:01.525
There's an electric field in
that direction,

00:49:01.525 --> 00:49:03.099
at least, but that's not
allowed.

00:49:03.099 --> 00:49:06.250
So V is a constant,
so take any metal shaped like

00:49:06.250 --> 00:49:06.880
anything.
 

00:49:06.880 --> 00:49:12.217
You can associate a single
potential to all of it,

00:49:12.217 --> 00:49:12.980
okay?
 

00:49:12.980 --> 00:49:15.000
If it's got charge on it that's
the same,

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:18.335
and what it means if you start
at infinity the work done to

00:49:18.335 --> 00:49:20.853
come there,
the work done to come there,

00:49:20.853 --> 00:49:24.706
the work done to come there are
all the same because they're all

00:49:24.706 --> 00:49:26.360
measuring the potential.
 

00:49:26.360 --> 00:49:29.360
The whole metal is at one
potential.

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:31.510
That allows you to do certain
tricks.

00:49:31.510 --> 00:49:33.679
So here's one trick you do.
 

00:49:33.679 --> 00:49:36.440
There are more tricks,
but this is the only one we can

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:37.690
discuss in this class.
 

00:49:37.690 --> 00:49:41.353
So here's an infinite
conducting plane,

00:49:41.353 --> 00:49:45.210
a sort of ground,
attached to the ground,

00:49:45.210 --> 00:49:48.969
and over this guy I put a
charge q.

00:49:48.969 --> 00:49:52.858
And I ask you,
"Find the electric field

00:49:52.858 --> 00:49:54.940
everywhere now."
 

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:58.349
That's your challenge.
 

00:49:58.349 --> 00:50:01.985
Without this guy fields are
just radial, so radial,

00:50:01.985 --> 00:50:05.911
radial, but the fields come
near this metal they cannot

00:50:05.911 --> 00:50:06.929
penetrate.
 

00:50:06.929 --> 00:50:10.329
They've got to stop at the
surface of the metal.

00:50:10.329 --> 00:50:15.090
So the field lines will do that.
 

00:50:15.090 --> 00:50:17.925
They will all terminate on the
metal, and to terminate you need

00:50:17.925 --> 00:50:20.485
some negative charge which the
metal will suck out of the

00:50:20.485 --> 00:50:20.989
ground.
 

00:50:20.989 --> 00:50:24.710
That's the reason for grounding
it.

00:50:24.710 --> 00:50:30.280
So the question is what kind of
charge distribution do you get

00:50:30.280 --> 00:50:31.650
on the metal?
 

00:50:31.650 --> 00:50:34.530
How much charge is there on the
metal?

00:50:34.530 --> 00:50:37.931
And because there are positive
charge and negative charge here

00:50:37.931 --> 00:50:41.112
what's the force of attraction
between this charge and the

00:50:41.112 --> 00:50:41.670
plane?
 

00:50:41.670 --> 00:50:44.559
In general that's a very
difficult problem.

00:50:44.559 --> 00:50:47.119
If I gave you a potato,
aluminum potato,

00:50:47.119 --> 00:50:50.074
put a charge next to it,
it will have a force,

00:50:50.074 --> 00:50:52.570
but it's not easy to calculate
it.

00:50:52.570 --> 00:50:57.480
But this infinite sheet turns
out very easy to calculate.

00:50:57.480 --> 00:51:02.436
The reason is that we can solve
this problem by borrowing from

00:51:02.436 --> 00:51:03.900
another problem.
 

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:06.389
The problem I borrow from is
the following.

00:51:06.389 --> 00:51:08.280
Forget this plane.
 

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:12.992
Continue these lines,
and think of the problem of a

00:51:12.992 --> 00:51:17.139
dipole with an equal negative
charge here.

00:51:17.139 --> 00:51:20.860
So the lines from them go like
this, right?

00:51:20.860 --> 00:51:23.869
And if you slice it in the
perpendicular bisector of this

00:51:23.869 --> 00:51:27.309
distance between them you will
hit every line perpendicularly.

00:51:27.309 --> 00:51:29.880
You guys remember that part
about the dipole field at

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:30.768
somewhere there?
 

00:51:30.768 --> 00:51:33.719
You cut it right down the
middle.

00:51:33.719 --> 00:51:43.349
So this plane was an
equipotential at V = 0.

00:51:43.349 --> 00:51:45.940
If it's an equipotential there
is nothing there.

00:51:45.940 --> 00:51:48.831
It was just a mathematical
surface on which V was

00:51:48.831 --> 00:51:50.199
constant and equal to 0.
 

00:51:50.199 --> 00:51:53.806
If V is constant you can
slide in a conductor there and

00:51:53.806 --> 00:51:56.460
nobody will know,
because the field is 0 along

00:51:56.460 --> 00:52:01.550
the surface of the conductor,
nothing happens.

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:04.510
So you can reconcile the fact
that conductors are

00:52:04.510 --> 00:52:07.226
equipotentials,
and solve problems in which a

00:52:07.226 --> 00:52:10.273
charge is in front of a
conductor if you're lucky enough

00:52:10.273 --> 00:52:13.487
to find the situation where
that's an equipotential surface

00:52:13.487 --> 00:52:16.644
of the same shape as your
conductor then you can slip your

00:52:16.644 --> 00:52:17.920
conductor there.
 

00:52:17.920 --> 00:52:22.445
So in this example what happens
is that the electric field here

00:52:22.445 --> 00:52:26.681
throughout the plane is exactly
what you would get due to a

00:52:26.681 --> 00:52:28.579
dipole minus and plus.
 

00:52:28.579 --> 00:52:33.000
That you can easily calculate
at all points on the plane.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.815
And once you've got the
electric field you remember

00:52:35.815 --> 00:52:38.630
σ/ε
_0 is the

00:52:38.630 --> 00:52:41.110
electric field so you can find
σ,

00:52:41.110 --> 00:52:44.840
the charge density.
 

00:52:44.840 --> 00:52:48.731
And if you integrate the charge
density you will get exactly

00:52:48.731 --> 00:52:51.362
-q,
because the number of lines

00:52:51.362 --> 00:52:54.846
coming from here have to
terminate on the plane rather

00:52:54.846 --> 00:52:57.539
than on this and that'll be
-q.

00:52:57.539 --> 00:53:00.365
And finally,
what's the force of attraction

00:53:00.365 --> 00:53:02.789
between the plane and this
