01:03:45.230 --> 01:03:47.539
And because it's harder and
harder to pump the coulombs you

01:03:47.539 --> 01:03:49.731
can imagine that there is a
potential difference between

01:03:49.731 --> 01:03:52.027
them,
because you've got to go uphill

01:03:52.027 --> 01:03:55.639
to pump even more charge into
this already charged object.

01:03:55.639 --> 01:03:59.253
So we define the capacitance as
the charge that you transferred

01:03:59.253 --> 01:04:01.820
divided by the voltage
difference you got.

01:04:01.820 --> 01:04:04.030
So let me call this 0 by
convention.

01:04:04.030 --> 01:04:08.969
That is called the capacitance.
 

01:04:08.969 --> 01:04:12.460
That's the ability of that
system to hold charge.

01:04:12.460 --> 01:04:14.326
If they're very,
very tiny metal spheres there's

01:04:14.326 --> 01:04:15.199
some amount of work.
 

01:04:15.199 --> 01:04:19.418
If they're huge metal spheres
you can transfer a lot of

01:04:19.418 --> 01:04:20.590
charge, okay?
 

01:04:20.590 --> 01:04:21.550
That's the definition.
 

01:04:21.550 --> 01:04:24.349
It's measured in farads.
 

01:04:24.349 --> 01:04:26.835
Again, it's got some units
coulomb for volt,

01:04:26.835 --> 01:04:30.304
but again it's got a different
name, named after Mr. Faraday,

01:04:30.304 --> 01:04:31.750
measured in farads.
 

01:04:31.750 --> 01:04:34.969
Usually you will have
microfarads in a lab.

01:04:34.969 --> 01:04:38.199
Farad is a huge unit.
 

01:04:38.199 --> 01:04:42.869
So let's find the capacitance
of certain simple arrangements.

01:04:42.869 --> 01:04:47.570
Simplest arrangement is the
parallel plate capacitor.

01:04:47.570 --> 01:04:48.440
Here it is.
 

01:04:48.440 --> 01:04:50.710
There's one plate.
 

01:04:50.710 --> 01:04:52.829
Here's a second plate.
 

01:04:52.829 --> 01:04:54.969
The area of the plate is
